STREPTOCOCCUS, GROUP A - AUSTRALIA: (QUEENSLAND) NOSOCOMIAL, FATAL
******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 13 Dec 2013
Source: The Courier Mail [edited]
http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/two-patients-die-in-streptococcal-outbreak-at-brisbanes-greenslopes-private-hospital/story-fnihsrf2-1226782037272


The deaths of 2 patients in a [Queensland] hospital have been linked to an outbreak of the _Streptococcus_ [group] A bacteria. A bacterial outbreak at a Brisbane private hospital has killed 2 patients and infected at least 2 others, forcing authorities to lock down part of the facility. Greenslopes Private Hospital, on Brisbane's south, had last night [night of 12 Dec 2013] isolated its rehabilitation unit from the rest of the facility and suspended all admissions.

Two men, aged in their 90s, have died from the streptococcus A infections with another 2 patients testing positive to the bacteria. Authorities are testing all patients and staff in the unit for the bacteria, including those who had been discharged in the past 2 weeks. Queensland Health has been notified of the infections and the deaths of the 2 men.

_Streptococcus_ [group] A is a bacterium often found in the throat and on the skin. People can carry the bacteria without becoming sick and some develop minor symptoms such as a sore throat. But in rare cases the bacteria can invade the bloodstream or the lungs and can cause severe, life-threatening illnesses, particularly in the elderly. A Greenslopes Hospital spokeswoman said _Streptococcus_ [group] A could be spread from person to person via respiratory droplets and close contact with someone carrying the bacteria. "Most people who come into contact with Group A _Streptococcus_ remain well and symptom free,'' she said. The spokeswoman said once identified, the infection could be successfully treated with antibiotics.

Patients and visitors to the Greenslopes hospital rehabilitation unit since [29 Nov 2013] are advised to phone 3394 7826.

[Byline: Janelle Miles]

