[The following is mostly extracted from moderator ML's comments in ProMED-mail post Streptococcus, group A, nosocomial - China: (HK) 20081231.4135:

Group A streptococci (GAS, also known as _Streptococcus pyogenes_) are an uncommon but important cause of nosocomial infections. GAS can be highly contagious and prior ProMED-mail posts -- archive numbers 20080206.0484 and 20050308.0692 -- have reported spread of group A streptococcal disease in health care settings among susceptible patients and health care workers.

The news release above does not state whether the cases had any underlying diseases, such as open wounds, recent surgery, diabetes, or immune deficiency, which would make patients particularly vulnerable to GAS infection, though the elderly and those with underlying medical conditions are at greatest risk for invasive GAS infections, which tend to be more severe and may be complicated by shock, multisystem organ failure, and death.

Some strains of GAS are more virulent than others. Tissue invasiveness of GAS has been attributed to several virulence factors, especially the cell wall M protein, encoded by the _emm_ gene. Strains have been typed based on the antigenic specificity of its M protein. More recently GAS are typed on the basis of sequence analysis of the portion of the _emm_ gene that encodes M serospecificity (http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/biotech/strep/M-ProteinGene_typing.htm). Epidemiologic studies in the US suggest that a significant percentage of the serious sequelae of group A streptococcal infections are associated with a relatively small number of specific emm/M protein types.

Other molecular techniques to further characterize outbreak strains include pulse-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE) of chromosomal DNA fragments, multilocus sequence typing (MLST), and detection of exotoxin-encoding genes (http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0195670197901948, http://www.jstor.org/pss/30128192, http://iai.asm.org/cgi/content/short/69/4/2416, and http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20687911). Molecular analysis of the isolates will aid documenting a common source outbreak. The source of a nosocomial outbreak may be an asymptomatic patient or even a healthcare worker who carries GAS either in the anus, vagina, skin, or pharynx and can shed the organism into the immediate environment despite proper gowning and gloving (see http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00056612.htm). - Mod.ML

The state of Queensland can be seen on the map of Australia at http://www.ga.gov.au/image_cache/GA4073.jpg. Brisbane and Greenslopes Private Hospital can be located via the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at http://healthmap.org/r/9wo_. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
